# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: netconf-yang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The **Network Configuration Protocol** (**NETCONF**) is a network management protocol developed and standardized by the IETF.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] It was developed in the NETCONF working group and published in December 2006 as RFC 4741 and later revised in June 2011 and published as RFC 6241.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The NETCONF protocol specification is an Internet Standards Track document.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] NETCONF provides mechanisms to install, manipulate, and delete the configuration of network devices.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Its operations are realized on top of a simple Remote Procedure Call (RPC) layer.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The NETCONF protocol uses an Extensible Markup Language (XML) based data encoding for the configuration data as well as the protocol messages.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The protocol messages are exchanged on top of a secure transport protocol.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The Operations layer defines a set of base protocol operations to retrieve and edit the configuration data.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The Messages layer provides a mechanism for encoding remote procedure calls (RPCs) and notifications.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The Secure Transport layer provides a secure and reliable transport of messages between a client and a server.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The NETCONF protocol has been implemented in network devices such as routers and switches by some major equipment vendors.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] One particular strength of NETCONF is its support for robust configuration change using transactions involving a number of devices.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The IETF developed the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) in the late 1980s and it proved to be a very popular network management protocol.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] In the early part of the 21st century it became apparent that in spite of what was originally intended, SNMP was not being used to configure network equipment, but was mainly being used for network monitoring.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] In June 2002, the Internet Architecture Board and key members of the IETF's network management community got together with network operators to discuss the situation.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The results of this meeting are documented in RFC 3535.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] It turned out that each network operator was primarily using a different proprietary command-line interface (CLI) to configure their devices.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] This had a number of features that the operators liked, including the fact that it was text-based, as opposed to the BER-encoded SNMP.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] In addition, many equipment vendors did not provide the option to completely configure their devices via SNMP.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] As operators generally liked to write scripts to help manage their boxes, they found the SNMP CLI lacking in a number of ways.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Most notably was the unpredictable nature of the output.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The content and formatting of output was prone to change in unpredictable ways.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Around this same time, Juniper Networks had been using an XML-based network management approach.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] This was brought to the IETF and shared with the broader community.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Collectively, these two events led the IETF in May 2003 to the creation of the NETCONF working group.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] This working group was chartered to work on a network configuration protocol, which would better align with the needs of network operators and equipment vendors.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The first version of the base NETCONF protocol was published as RFC 4741 in December 2006.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Several extensions were published in subsequent years (notifications in RFC 5277 in July 2008, partial locks in RFC 5717 in December 2009, with-defaults in RFC 6243 in June 2011, system notifications in RFC 6470 in February 2012, access control in RFC 6536 in March 2012).
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] A revised version of the base NETCONF protocol was published as RFC 6241 in June 2011.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The content of NETCONF operations is well-formed XML.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Most content is related to network management.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Subsequently, support for encoding in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) was also added.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The NETMOD working group has completed work to define a "human-friendly" modeling language for defining the semantics of operational data, configuration data, notifications, and operations, called YANG.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] YANG is defined in RFC 6020 (version 1) and RFC 7950 (version 1.1), and is accompanied by the "Common YANG Data Types" found in RFC 6991.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] During the summer of 2010, the NETMOD working group was re-chartered to work on core configuration models (system, interface, and routing) as well as work on compatibility with the SNMP modeling language.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Basic NETCONF functionality can be extended by the definition of NETCONF capabilities.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] The set of additional protocol features that an implementation supports is communicated between the server and the client during the capability exchange portion of session setup.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Mandatory protocol features are not included in the capability exchange since they are assumed.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] RFC 4741 defines a number of optional capabilities including :xpath and :validate.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] A capability to support subscribing and receiving asynchronous event notifications is published in RFC 5277.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] This document defines the <create-subscription> operation, which enables creating real-time and replay subscriptions.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Notifications are then sent asynchronously using the <notification> construct.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] It also defines the :interleave capability, which when supported with the basic :notification capability facilitates the processing of other NETCONF operations while the subscription is active.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] A capability to support partial locking of the running configuration is defined in RFC 5717.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] This allows multiple sessions to edit non-overlapping sub-trees within the running configuration.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Without this capability, the only lock available is for the entire configuration.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] A capability to monitor the NETCONF protocol is defined in RFC 6022.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] This document contains a data model including information about NETCONF datastores, sessions, locks, and statistics that facilitates the management of a NETCONF server.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] It also defines methods for NETCONF clients to discover data models supported by a NETCONF server and defines the <get-schema> operation to retrieve them.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] Every NETCONF message is a well-formed XML document.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] An RPC result is linked to an RPC invocation by a message-id attribute.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] NETCONF messages can be pipelined, i.e., a client can invoke multiple RPCs without having to wait for RPC result messages first.
[src:netconf-yang/netconf] RPC messages are defined in RFC 6241 and notification messages are defined in RFC 5277.
[src:netconf-yang/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:netconf-yang/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:netconf-yang/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:netconf-yang/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:netconf-yang/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:netconf-yang/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:netconf-yang/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:netconf-yang/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Google developed Protocol Buffers for internal use and provided a code generator for multiple languages under an open-source license.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The design goals for Protocol Buffers emphasized simplicity and performance.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] In particular, it was designed to be smaller and faster than XML.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is widely used at Google for storing and interchanging all kinds of structured information.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The method serves as a basis for a custom remote procedure call (RPC) system that is used for nearly all inter-machine communication at Google.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is similar to the Apache Thrift, Amazon Ion, and Microsoft Bond protocols, offering a concrete RPC protocol stack to use for defined services called gRPC.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Data structure schemas (called *messages*) and services are described in a proto definition file (`.proto`) and compiled with `protoc`.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] This compilation generates code that can be invoked by a sender or recipient of these data structures.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] For example, `example.pb.cc` and `example.pb.h` are generated from `example.proto`.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] They define C++ classes for each message and service in `example.proto`.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Canonically, messages are serialized into a binary wire format which is compact, forward- and backward-compatible, but not self-describing (that is, there is no way to tell the names, meaning, or full datatypes of fields without an external specification).
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] There is no defined way to include or refer to such an external specification (schema) within a Protocol Buffers file.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The officially supported implementation includes an ASCII serialization format, but this format—though self-describing—loses the forward- and backward-compatibility behavior, and is thus not a good choice for applications other than human editing and debugging.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Though the primary purpose of Protocol Buffers is to facilitate network communication, its simplicity and speed make Protocol Buffers an alternative to data-centric C++ classes and structs, especially where interoperability with other languages or systems might be needed in the future.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The format is best suited for small data chunks that don't exceed a few megabytes and can be loaded/sent into memory right away and therefore is not a streamable format.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The library doesn't provide compression out of the box.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The format also isn't well supported in non–object-oriented languages (e.g.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] A schema for a particular use of protocol buffers associates data types with field names, using integers to identify each field.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The `Point` message defines two mandatory data items, `x` and `y`.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The tag is defined after the equal sign.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] The `Line` and `Polyline` messages, which both use `Point`, demonstrate how composition works in Protocol Buffers.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] `Polyline` has a `repeated` field, and thus `Polyline` behaves like a set of points (of unspecified number).
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] This schema can subsequently be compiled for use by one or more programming languages.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Google provides a compiler called `protoc` which can produce output for C++, Java or Python.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Other schema compilers are available from other sources to create language-dependent output for over 20 other languages.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 2.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java, C#, and Python.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 3.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java (including JavaNano, a dialect intended for low-resource environments), Kotlin, Python, Go, Ruby, Objective-C, C#, PHP, Dart.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] It also supports JavaScript since 3.0.0-beta-2.
[src:netconf-yang/protocol-buffers] Third-party implementations are also available for Ada, Ballerina, C, C++, Dart, Elixir, Erlang, Haskell, JavaScript, Julia, Nim, Perl, PHP, Prolog, R, Rust, Scala, and Swift.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:netconf-yang/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is widely used in network management for network monitoring.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP exposes management data in the form of variables on the managed systems organized in a management information base (MIB), which describes the system status and configuration.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] These variables can then be remotely queried (and, in some circumstances, manipulated) by network management applications.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Three significant versions of SNMP have been developed and deployed.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 is the original version of the protocol.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] More recent versions, SNMPv2c and SNMPv3, feature improvements in performance, flexibility and security.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is a component of the Internet Protocol Suite as defined by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] It consists of a set of standards for network management, including an application layer protocol, a database schema, and a set of data objects.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] In typical uses of SNMP, one or more administrative computers called *managers* have the task of monitoring or managing a group of hosts or devices on a computer network.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Each managed system executes a software component called an *agent* that reports information via SNMP to the manager.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A *managed device* is a network node that implements an SNMP interface that allows unidirectional (read-only) or bidirectional (read and write) access to node-specific information.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Managed devices exchange node-specific information with the NMSs.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Sometimes called network elements, the managed devices can be any type of device, including, but not limited to, routers, access servers, switches, cable modems, bridges, hubs, IP telephones, IP video cameras, computer hosts, and printers.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] An *agent* is a network-management software module that resides on a managed device.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] An agent has local knowledge of management information and translates that information to or from an SNMP-specific form.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A *network management station* executes applications that monitor and control managed devices.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] NMSs provide the bulk of the processing and memory resources required for network management.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] One or more NMSs may exist on any managed network.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP agents expose management data on the managed systems as variables.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The protocol also permits active management tasks, such as configuration changes, through remote modification of these variables.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The variables accessible via SNMP are organized in hierarchies.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP itself does not define which variables a managed system should offer.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Rather, SNMP uses an extensible design that allows applications to define their own hierarchies.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] These hierarchies are described as a management information base (MIB).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] MIBs describe the structure of the management data of a device subsystem; they use a hierarchical namespace containing object identifiers (OID).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Each OID identifies a variable that can be read or set via SNMP.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] MIBs use the notation defined by Structure of Management Information Version 2.0 (SMIv2, RFC 2578), a subset of ASN.1.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP operates in the application layer of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] All SNMP messages are transported via User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The SNMP agent receives requests on UDP port 161.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The manager may send requests from any available source port to port 161 in the agent.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The agent response is sent back to the source port on the manager.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The manager receives notifications (*Traps* and *InformRequests*) on port 162.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The agent may generate notifications from any available port.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] When used with Transport Layer Security or Datagram Transport Layer Security, requests are received on port 10161 and notifications are sent to port 10162.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 specifies five core protocol data units (PDUs).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Two other PDUs, *GetBulkRequest* and *InformRequest* were added in SNMPv2 and the *Report* PDU was added in SNMPv3.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to retrieve the value of a variable or list of variables.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Desired variables are specified in variable bindings (the value field is not used).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to change the value of a variable or list of variables.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Variable bindings are specified in the body of the request.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Changes to all specified variables are to be made as an atomic operation by the agent.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] with (current) new values for the variables is returned.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to discover available variables and their values.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Rows of a table can be read by specifying column OIDs in the variable bindings of the request.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] with multiple variable bindings walked from the variable binding or bindings in the request.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] fields are used to control response behavior.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Asynchronous notification from agent to manager.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] While in other SNMP communication, the manager actively requests information from the agent, these are PDUs that are sent from the agent to the manager without being explicitly requested.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] enable an agent to notify the management station of significant events by way of an unsolicited SNMP message.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] value, an OID identifying the type of trap and optional variable bindings.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Destination addressing for traps is determined in an application-specific manner, typically through trap configuration variables in the MIB.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] fixes this as an acknowledgement is returned on receipt.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] RFC 1157 specifies that an SNMP implementation must accept a message of at least 484 bytes in length.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] In practice, SNMP implementations accept longer messages.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] If implemented correctly, an SNMP message is discarded if the decoding of the message fails and thus malformed SNMP requests are ignored.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A successfully decoded SNMP request is then authenticated using the community string.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] If the authentication fails, a trap is generated indicating an authentication failure and the message is dropped.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 and SNMPv2c use *communities* to establish trust between managers and agents.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Most agents support three community names, one each for read-only, read-write and trap.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] These three *community strings* control different types of activities.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The read-only community applies to *get* requests.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The read-write community string applies to *set* requests.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The trap community string applies to receipt of *traps*.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 also uses community strings, but allows for secure authentication and communication between SNMP manager and agent.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] In practice, SNMP implementations often support multiple versions: typically SNMPv1, SNMPv2c, and SNMPv3.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP version 1 (SNMPv1) is the initial implementation of the SNMP protocol.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The design of SNMPv1 was done in the 1980s by a group of collaborators who viewed the officially sponsored OSI/IETF/NSF (National Science Foundation) effort (HEMS/CMIS/CMIP) as both unimplementable in the computing platforms of the time as well as potentially unworkable.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP was approved based on a belief that it was an interim protocol needed for taking steps towards large-scale deployment of the Internet and its commercialization.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 is widely used and is the de facto network management protocol in the Internet community.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 may be carried by transport layer protocols such as User Datagram Protocol (UDP), OSI Connectionless-mode Network Service (CLNS), AppleTalk Datagram Delivery Protocol (DDP), and Novell Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Version 1 has been criticized for its poor security.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] For example, an organization may consider their internal network to be sufficiently secure that no encryption is necessary for its SNMP messages.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] In such cases, the *community name*, which is transmitted in cleartext, tends to be viewed as a de facto password, in spite of the original specification.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2, defined by RFC 1441 and RFC 1452, revises version 1 and includes improvements in the areas of performance, security and manager-to-manager communications.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] It introduced *GetBulkRequest*, an alternative to iterative GetNextRequests for retrieving large amounts of management data in a single request.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The new party-based security system introduced in SNMPv2, viewed by many as overly complex, was not widely adopted.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] This version of SNMP reached the Proposed Standard level of maturity, but was deemed obsolete by later versions.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP version 2 introduces the option for 64-bit data counters.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Version 1 was designed only with 32-bit counters, which can store integer values from zero to 4.29 billion (precisely 4294967295).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A 32-bit version 1 counter cannot store the maximum speed of a 10-gigabit or larger interface, expressed in bits per second.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Similarly, a 32-bit counter tracking statistics for a 10-gigabit or larger interface can roll over back to zero again in less than one minute, which may be a shorter time interval than a counter is polled to read its current state.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] This would result in lost or invalid data due to the undetected value rollover and corruption of trend-tracking data.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The 64-bit version 2 counter can store values from zero to 18.4 quintillion (precisely 18,446,744,073,709,551,615) and so is currently unlikely to experience a counter rollover between polling events.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] For example, 1.6 terabit Ethernet is predicted to become available by 2025.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A 64-bit counter incrementing at a rate of 1.6 trillion bits per second would be able to retain information for such an interface without rolling over for 133 days.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c is incompatible with SNMPv1 in two key areas: message formats and protocol operations.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c messages use a different header and different protocol data unit (PDU) formats than SNMPv1 messages.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c also uses two protocol operations that are not specified in SNMPv1.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] To overcome incompatibility, RFC 3584 defines two SNMPv1/v2c coexistence strategies: proxy agents and bilingual network-management systems.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] An SNMPv2 agent can act as a proxy agent on behalf of SNMPv1-managed devices.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] When an SNMPv2 NMS issues a command intended for an SNMPv1 agent, it sends it to the SNMPv2 proxy agent instead.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The proxy agent forwards `Get`, `GetNext`, and `Set` messages to the SNMPv1 agent unchanged.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] `GetBulk` messages are converted by the proxy agent to `GetNext` messages and then are forwarded to the SNMPv1 agent.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Additionally, the proxy agent receives and maps SNMPv1 trap messages to SNMPv2 trap messages and then forwards them to the NMS.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Bilingual SNMPv2 network-management systems support both SNMPv1 and SNMPv2.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] To support this dual-management environment, a management application examines information stored in a local database to determine whether the agent supports SNMPv1 or SNMPv2.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Based on the information in the database, the NMS communicates with the agent using the appropriate version of SNMP.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Although SNMPv3 makes no changes to the protocol aside from the addition of cryptographic security, it looks very different due to new textual conventions, concepts, and terminology.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The most visible change was to define a secure version of SNMP, by adding security and remote configuration enhancements to SNMP.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The security aspect is addressed by offering both strong authentication and data encryption for privacy.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] For the administration aspect, SNMPv3 focuses on two parts, namely notification originators and proxy forwarders.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The changes also facilitate remote configuration and administration of the SNMP entities, as well as addressing issues related to the large-scale deployment, accounting, and fault management.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Security was one of the biggest weaknesses of SNMP until v3.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Authentication in SNMP Versions 1 and 2 amounts to nothing more than a password (community string) sent in clear text between a manager and agent.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Each SNMPv3 message contains security parameters that are encoded as an octet string.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The meaning of these security parameters depends on the security model being used.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] v3 also defines the USM and VACM, which were later followed by a transport security model (TSM) that provided support for SNMPv3 over SSH and SNMPv3 over TLS and DTLS.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] As of 2004 the IETF recognizes *Simple Network Management Protocol version 3* as defined by RFC 3411–RFC 3418 (also known as STD0062) as the current standard version of SNMP.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The IETF has designated SNMPv3 a full Internet standard, the highest maturity level for an RFC.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] It considers earlier versions to be obsolete (designating them variously *Historic* or *Obsolete*).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Some SNMP values (especially tabular values) require specific knowledge of table indexing schemes, and these index values are not necessarily consistent across platforms.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Some major equipment vendors tend to over-extend their proprietary command line interface (CLI) centric configuration and control systems.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] In February 2002 the Carnegie Mellon Software Engineering Institute (CM-SEI) Computer Emergency Response Team Coordination Center (CERT-CC) issued an Advisory on SNMPv1, after the Oulu University Secure Programming Group conducted a thorough analysis of SNMP message handling.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Most SNMP implementations, regardless of which version of the protocol they support, use the same program code for decoding protocol data units (PDU) and problems were identified in this code.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Other problems were found with decoding SNMP trap messages received by the SNMP management station or requests received by the SNMP agent on the network device.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Many vendors had to issue patches for their SNMP implementations.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Because SNMP is designed to allow administrators to monitor and configure network devices remotely, it can also be used to penetrate a network.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] A significant number of software tools can scan the entire network using SNMP; therefore, mistakes in the configuration of the read-write mode can make a network susceptible to attacks.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] In 2001, Cisco released information that indicated that, even in read-only mode, the SNMP implementation of Cisco IOS is vulnerable to certain denial of service attacks.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] These security issues can be fixed through an IOS upgrade.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] If SNMP is not used in a network, it should be disabled in network devices.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] When configuring SNMP read-only mode, close attention should be paid to the configuration of the access control and from which IP addresses SNMP messages are accepted.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] If the SNMP servers are identified by their IP addresses, SNMP is only allowed to respond to these IPs and SNMP messages from other IP addresses would be denied.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] However, IP address spoofing remains a security concern.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is available in different versions, and each version has its own security issues.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v1 sends passwords in plaintext over the network.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Therefore, passwords can be read with packet sniffing.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v2 allows password hashing with MD5, but this has to be configured.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Virtually all network management software support SNMP v1, but not necessarily SNMP v2 or v3.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v2 was specifically developed to provide data security, that is authentication, privacy and authorization, but only SNMP version 2c gained the endorsement of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), while versions 2u and 2* failed to gain IETF approval due to security issues.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v3 uses MD5, Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA) and keyed algorithms to offer protection against unauthorized data modification and spoofing attacks.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] If a higher level of security is needed the Data Encryption Standard (DES) can be optionally used in the cipher block chaining mode.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v3 is implemented on Cisco IOS since release 12.0(3)T.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 may be subject to brute force and dictionary attacks for guessing the authentication keys, or encryption keys, if these keys are generated from short (weak) passwords or passwords that can be found in a dictionary.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 allows both providing random uniformly distributed cryptographic keys and generating cryptographic keys from a password supplied by the user.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The risk of guessing authentication strings from hash values transmitted over the network depends on the cryptographic hash function used and the length of the hash value.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 uses the HMAC-SHA-2 authentication protocol for the User-based Security Model (USM).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP does not use a more secure challenge-handshake authentication protocol.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 (like other SNMP protocol versions) is a stateless protocol, and it has been designed with a minimal amount of interactions between the agent and the manager.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Thus introducing a challenge-response handshake for each command would impose a burden on the agent (and possibly on the network itself) that the protocol designers deemed excessive and unacceptable.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The security deficiencies of all SNMP versions can be mitigated by IPsec authentication and confidentiality mechanisms.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP also may be carried securely over Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS).
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Many SNMP implementations include a type of automatic discovery where a new network component, such as a switch or router, is discovered and polled automatically.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] In SNMPv1 and SNMPv2c, this is done through a *community string* that is transmitted in clear-text to other devices.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Clear-text passwords are a significant security risk.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Once the community string is known outside the organization, it could become the target for an attack.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] To alert administrators of other attempts to glean community strings, SNMP can be configured to pass community-name authentication failure traps.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] If SNMPv2 is used, the issue can be avoided by enabling password encryption on the SNMP agents of network devices.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] The common default configuration for community strings are "public" for read-only access and "private" for read-write.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Because of the well-known defaults, SNMP topped the list of the SANS Institute's Common Default Configuration Issues and was number ten on the SANS Top 10 Most Critical Internet Security Threats for the year 2000.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] System and network administrators frequently do not change these configurations.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] Whether it runs over TCP or UDP, SNMPv1 and v2 are vulnerable to IP spoofing attacks.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] With spoofing, attackers may bypass device access lists in agents that are implemented to restrict SNMP access.
[src:netconf-yang/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 security mechanisms, such as USM or TSM, can prevent spoofing attacks.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] YANG enables comprehensive network automation by providing a standardized way to model the configuration and state data of network elements.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The language can be used to define the format of event notifications emitted by network devices and allows data modelers to define the signature of RPCs that can be invoked on network elements via the NETCONF protocol.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] Being protocol-independent, YANG models can be converted into various encoding formats, including XML, JSON, and CBOR, depending on the network configuration protocol's support.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] YANG is a modular language and represents data structures in a hierarchical tree format.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] It includes numerous built-in data types, with the capability for users to derive additional application-specific types.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] More complex reusable data structures can be represented as "groupings," which promote model reusability and consistency.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] YANG data models can use XPath expressions to define constraints on the elements of a YANG data model, enabling validation of configuration data before it is committed to devices.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] YANG has become the de facto standard for modeling network device configurations across the telecommunications industry and is widely supported by major network equipment manufacturers.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] It plays a crucial role in software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) environments by providing a consistent interface for programmatic network management.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] Many network management protocols have associated data modeling languages.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The first widely deployed Internet standard for network management was the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The data modeling language associated with SNMP was called the Structure of Management Information (SMI).
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The SMI language itself was based on the 1988 version of the Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1).
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The current version of the SMI language, SMIv2 defined in RFC 2578, 2579 and 2580, has developed into an extended subset of ASN.1.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] In the late 1990s, a project was started to create a replacement for SMIv2, which was called SMIng.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] One motivation was to decouple SMIng from the management protocol SNMP and to give SMIng a syntactic structure that is both easy to parse for computer programs and easy to learn for people familiar with programming languages that use a C-like notation.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] While the SMIng project did not succeed in the IETF, the SMIng specifications were published as experimental documents in May 2004 (RFC 3780, 3781).
[src:netconf-yang/yang] Soon after the development of the NETCONF protocol in the IETF, it became clear that a data modeling language was needed to define data models manipulated by the NETCONF protocol.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] A design team created a proposal that became the basis of the YANG language.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The syntactic structure and the base type system was essentially borrowed from SMIng.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] However, based on the lessons learned from the SMIng project, no attempts were made to make the YANG protocol neutral.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] Instead, YANG ties into concepts of the NETCONF protocol, such as the assumption that data model instances can be serialized into XML.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] Standardization of YANG started with the formation of the NETMOD working group in April 2008.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The YANG 1.0 specification was published as RFC 6020 in October 2010.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] Recently, the NETMOD working group has been working on YANG 1.1, which has been published in August 2016 in RFC 7950.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The following YANG module `example-sports` shows a data model for team sports.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The module declares a namespace and a prefix and imports the type library module `ietf-yang-types` before defining the type `season`.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] It then defines a container `sports` that includes a list of `person`s and a list of `team`s.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] A team has a list of players that reference persons via the `leafref` type and its `path` restriction.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The code block below shows the JSON representation of an instantiation of the `example-sports` data model.
[src:netconf-yang/yang] The code block below shows the XML representation of an instantiation of the `example-sports` data model.
